@elilevine You can also remove the exclusions on `avatica-core` from the `calcite-core` "normal" and test scope.

I'm surprised that you had to add avatica-core to the `ignoreUnusedDeclaredDependency` list (but verified its need myself). I guess the package-info.java file doesn't get picked up by the maven-dependency-plugin :). A comment in the pom.xml stating that it appears to be a dependency-plugin bug would be nice for future devs.

Otherwise, I think this is the right approach!

@axeisghost , thanks for the PR and the detailed description.

I have been reviewing it. One general concern I have is about the encapsulation of the solution. It seems that we are mixing code that should be logically separated, e.g., pushing computation to ```DruidQuery``` via rules vs generation of JSON for Druid. For instance, this results in needing to add a placeholder to ```DruidQuery``` to hold the JSON ```postAggs```.

Generation of the JSON code should still be encapsulated, thus one recommendation is to split the logic that validates/pushes computation to ```DruidQuery``` (this should still be done by ```DruidPostAggregationProjectRule```) from the logic that generates the JSON code (currently done within ```DruidQuery```). In addition to make the code of the rule more readable, that would also allow us to hold all the relational ops that we have pushed to ```DruidQuery``` within ```rels```. Currently the post-aggregation ```Project``` is removed, which means that we cannot obtain the equivalent relational expression that the ```DruidQuery``` is computing by looking at ```rels```. I think that is an interesting property to keep.

@jcamachor 
I just updated the branch. I made changes as you suggested. It is more clean now and redundant logics are removed. Please review anytime.
Thank you.

@pavelgubin You should definitely have updated RelOptRulesTest.xml if your current PR gives test errors. If you submit a PR for review we assume that all tests pass, unless you state otherwise. After all what's the use of a "fix" that breaks several other tests. The plan changes could be benign, but if the new plans are less efficient then we won't accept this PR.

Read the javadoc in RelOptRulesTest.java. It describes how to update RelOptRulesTest.xml.

It sounds like @michaelmior is +1 on this change. Please fix the tests, and I will squash / rebase / re-title and commit to master after 1.14 is released.
